===Etymology===
{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=k|そで}}
{{IPAfont|⟨so<sub>1</sub> te⟩}} → {{IPAchar|/so te/}} → {{IPAchar|/sode/}}

From {{inh|ja|ojp|sort=そて|-}}.  First attested in the ''{{w|Kojiki}}'' of 712 with the phonetic spelling {{m|ojp||蘇弖|pos={{IPAfont|⟨so₁ te⟩}}}}.<ref name="KDJ2">{{R:Nihon Kokugo Daijiten 2}}</ref>  {{rendaku2|sort=そで|te|de}}

Japanese references that include an etymology note that this appears to be a compound of {{compound|ja|衣|tr1=so|t1=robe; clothing|手|tr2=te|t2=hand; arm}}.<ref name="KDJ2"/><ref name="DJR"/><ref name="SMK5"/><ref name="K">{{R:Kojien}}</ref>  However, the initial ''so-'' is clearly spelled with the so-called {{m|ja|甲類|tr=kōrui||"A" type}} vowel {{IPAfont|⟨so₁⟩}} in the oldest texts, whereas {{m|ja|衣}} when read as ''so'' was pronounced with the so-called {{m|ja|乙類|tr=otsurui||"B" type}} vowel as {{IPAfont|⟨so₂⟩}}.  These were treated as separate vowels in Old Japanese, so this proposed compound cannot be the actual derivation.<ref name="KDJ2"/>

